               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-787" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-787" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-787" type="surname" value="STERNEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-787" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM STERNEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am horsekeeper to James Bugbee, of Palmer's-village, Westminster. On Saturday afternoon I saw the prisoner loading dung at my master's—the fork was missed—this is it (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>), I know it by the eye—it is James Bugbee's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-788" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-788" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-788" type="surname" value="RIGGLESFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-788" type="given" value="ROBERT HENRY"></interp>ROBERT HENRY RIGGLESFORD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, T</hi> 26). I took the prisoner at Stanwell, with this fork on his shoulder—I asked how he came by it—he said it was his, that he had been at work for Mr. Price; then, that it be<lb></lb>longed to Mr. Price; and then to Mr. Price's carter—I took him to the carter, who denied it—I took it to Mr. Bugbee.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence</hi>. I laid it down, with three others, and did not know which was Mr. Price's.</p>
